{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653069"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18559"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11291"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8496"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26191"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe detrusor muscle is essential for normal bladder function and micturition control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the detrusor muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smooth muscle in a single circular layer","Skeletal muscle under voluntary control","Striated muscle innervated by somatic nerves","Smooth muscle arranged in spiral, longitudinal, and circular layers","Mixed muscle fibres with both smooth and skeletal components"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis complex arrangement of \u003Cstrong\u003Esmooth muscle arranged in spiral, longitudinal, and circular layers\u003C/strong\u003E allows for efficient bladder emptying during micturition while maintaining continence and expanding during filling. The muscle is controlled primarily by autonomic innervation, with parasympathetic stimulation causing contraction via muscarinic receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal muscle under voluntary control\u003C/strong\u003E describes the external urethral sphincter rather than the detrusor, which is smooth muscle under autonomic control. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle in a single circular layer\u003C/strong\u003E oversimplifies the detrusor\u0027s complex multi-layered architecture that enables its functional versatility. \u003Cstrong\u003EStriated muscle innervated by somatic nerves\u003C/strong\u003E again confuses the detrusor with the external urethral sphincter, as the detrusor lacks striations and receives autonomic innervation. \u003Cstrong\u003EMixed muscle fibres with both smooth and skeletal components\u003C/strong\u003E inaccurately suggests a hybrid composition, when the detrusor consists purely of smooth muscle fibres.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The detrusor muscle is composed of smooth muscle fibres arranged in spiral, longitudinal, and circular layers.","Parasympathetic stimulation causes detrusor muscle contraction via muscarinic receptors.","The detrusor muscle maintains urinary continence and facilitates bladder emptying."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 26; pg. 325","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","i